{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":17433,"record_hash":"sha256:7fa1693acebd4203a21978244228fff9347183bb92ad70b39eb5486f9ce8ad16","timestamp":"2026-05-10T06:53:12.026Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah, I think your instinct is right, but I’d be pretty selective.\n\nMy take: most of these should stay strings for now. The POC is mostly transporting and lightly normalizing provider data, not interpreting it deeply yet. Enums are useful when we branch on the value or need to guarantee a closed set. A lot of these fields are intentionally open-ended.\n\nThe fields I would **not** enum right now:\n\n- `source_event_kind`: provider-specific and open-ended. An enum here would become fake completeness fast.\n- `provider`: mostly metadata, currently not behavior-driving.\n- `model`, `tool_version`, `source_name`, `content_text`, `timestamp`: plain data strings.\n- `session_key`, `source_key`, `record_hash`: these are domain identifiers, but wrapping all of them in newtypes would add boilerplate around GitMeta/string serialization for modest benefit.\n\nThe one field that *might* deserve a small type later is `role`.\n\n`role` has semantic meaning for the future use cases: rendering a transcript, continuing a conversation, distinguishing user prompts from assistant replies. A tiny enum like this could be defensible:\n\n```rust\nenum Role {\n    User,\n    Assistant,\n    System,\n    Tool,\n    Other(String),\n}\n```\n\nSerialized as the same string shape. But I would only do this once we actually branch/render/filter by role. Right now we just redact and store it, so `Option<String>` is acceptable.\n\nThe type that is already clearly earning its keep is `Agent`. We parse it at the CLI boundary, branch on it for transcript parsing, and serialize it intentionally. That’s exactly the kind of string value that should be an enum.\n\nSo my recommendation: **don’t add more enums yet**. Maybe do small naming clarifications instead, like `session_id` -> `provider_session_id`, because that would reduce ambiguity without adding machinery. The POC stays cleaner if we let types appear when behavior needs them, not merely because the stored value has a known-looking string.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T06:53:12.026Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}